mixed those together,

00:01:54.700 --> 00:01:57.950
he got a yellow precipitate.

00:01:57.950 --> 00:01:59.430
Let's color that in yellow.

00:02:03.350 --> 00:02:05.240
A precipitate is a solid.

00:02:05.240 --> 00:02:08.395
So how do we know what
this yellow solid is?

00:02:08.395 --> 00:02:09.770
Well, this is the
reaction that's

00:02:09.770 --> 00:02:11.560
called a double
displacement reaction.

00:02:14.900 --> 00:02:18.350
And in this kind of reaction,
the cation and anion pairs

00:02:18.350 --> 00:02:19.800
switch places.

00:02:19.800 --> 00:02:21.840
So what exactly does that mean?

00:02:21.840 --> 00:02:24.860
I'm going to use some
colors to help me out.

00:02:24.860 --> 00:02:30.350
So we've got cations and anions
in each of these compounds.

00:02:30.350 --> 00:02:32.790
The cations have
positive charge.

00:02:32.790 --> 00:02:39.050
So in this case, it's
lead, which has a 2+ charge

00:02:39.050 --> 00:02:45.740
and nitrate, NO3-.

00:02:45.740 --> 00:02:51.230
You need two of those to
have a neutral compound.

00:02:51.230 --> 00:02:58.100
Our other compound, over here,
has potassium, which has a +1.

00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:04.850
And our anion is
iodide, which is -1.

00:03:04.850 --> 00:03:09.950
When these two solutions
are mixed, we've got lead,

00:03:09.950 --> 00:03:10.770
which is our +2.

00:03:13.760 --> 00:03:16.245
And it's going to
react with iodide.

00:03:21.410 --> 00:03:25.040
We need two of them to
make it a neutral compound.

00:03:25.040 --> 00:03:33.780
And potassium nitrate, and we
just need one nitrate here.

00:03:33.780 --> 00:03:38.317
So our cations and anions
all switched places.

00:03:38.317 --> 00:03:40.650
We're going to need to balance
this equation let's throw

00:03:40.650 --> 00:03:44.400
some twos there and there.

00:03:44.400 --> 00:03:47.190
So how can we predict which
one of these two compounds

00:03:47.190 --> 00:03:49.290
is the yellow precipitate?

00:03:49.290 --> 00:03:52.560
