chemists mixed ions together.

00:03:52.560 --> 00:03:56.490
And they came up with solubility
tables, just like this one.

00:03:56.490 --> 00:03:57.990
Now this chart
basically shows us

00:03:57.990 --> 00:04:01.020
when these two ions, an ion
from this column and this column

00:04:01.020 --> 00:04:03.240
are mixed together,
is their product,

00:04:03.240 --> 00:04:06.810
a compound that they form,
soluble or insoluble in water?

00:04:06.810 --> 00:04:08.230
If it's soluble
in water, there's

00:04:08.230 --> 00:04:10.620
an aq for aqueous on the chart.

00:04:10.620 --> 00:04:13.770
And if it's insoluble in
water, there's an s for solid.

00:04:13.770 --> 00:04:19.680
So our two compounds that we
want to look at our lead iodide

00:04:19.680 --> 00:04:22.329
and potassium nitrate.

00:04:25.280 --> 00:04:26.930
So let's take a look.

00:04:26.930 --> 00:04:29.330
Potassium nitrate--
we've got potassium

00:04:29.330 --> 00:04:32.000
down here at the bottom.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:36.210
We've got nitrate
here at the top.

00:04:36.210 --> 00:04:42.710
When mixed together, aqueous
solution, soluble in water.

00:04:42.710 --> 00:04:46.910
So it's more likely that
our lead iodide would

00:04:46.910 --> 00:04:48.200
be the yellow precipitate.

00:04:48.200 --> 00:04:50.160
But let's see if that's true.

00:04:50.160 --> 00:04:55.145
Lead mixed with iodide--

00:04:57.780 --> 00:04:59.290
voila.

00:04:59.290 --> 00:05:02.130
It's a solid.

00:05:02.130 --> 00:05:04.440
So to recap,
solubility tables help

00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:07.770
chemists predict whether or
not a precipitate will form

00:05:07.770 --> 00:05:09.840
when two solutions are mixed.

00:05:09.840 --> 00:05:17.280
So going back to our equation
here, the lead iodide--

00:05:17.280 --> 00:05:21.480
